The walk is being held on December 29 – the day that ‘Nirbhaya’, a young gangrape victim in New Delhi, died after fighting for her life for 13 days in 2012

“After 2018 floods, Navy undertook a survey of various affected areas and found that Cheriya Kadamakudi was one of the most affected and poorly connected areas where any kind of aid/rehabilitation reaching was difficult. It was like a forgotten place," said the Navy spokesperson.

The work was started in April and the Navy had to stop the works for nearly two weeks due to the floods in August. Navy said that the bridge has a guaranteed life of 5 years but can last over 20 years with dedicated annual maintenance, periodic painting and inspection.

VAdm Chawla said that the personnel of the SNC were delightful as they could fulfill the promise made to the island residents. “It is a privilege for the Navy to be of service to the residents of Cheriya Kadmakkudi and it is a fitting gift for the people during Onam,” he said.

The bridge will be able to allow vehicles that weigh up to 3 tonnes to ply on it.The inaugural event was attended by Sapana Chawla, President Navy Wives Welfare Association (NWWA) Southern Region, Rear Admiral RJ Nadkarni, Chief of Staff and other Flag Officers of SNC.

With the new bridge, the residents of Cheriya Kadamakudi will now be able to access the mainland without having to resort to boats or ferry. The 3-metre wide, 49-metre long, completely metallic bridge was constructed at a cost of Rs.40.45 lakhs in six months.

The bridge was promised to be constructed by SNC in the aftermath of 2018 floods, to connect the island with the mainland as the only other existing bridge there was in a dilapidated state and declared unfit for use by the PWD.

The decades-long dream of Cheriya Kadamakudi residents to have a motorable bridge that could connect them to the mainland finally came true on Monday as a Steel Arch Bridge christened as ‘Navika Palam’ was inaugurated by Vice Admiral AK Chawla, Southern Naval Command chief. https://t.co/Qlp4rbcxoc

The machinery for the HMB includes pasteurization unit, refrigerators, deep freezers, hospital grade breast pumps, RO plant, sterilizing equipment and computers. The ambience of the HMB will be made conducive for donor mothers to lactate and donate.

The HMB will have WHO-standard facilities and certification. The bank to be set up at a cost of around Rs.35 lakh will be funded by Rotary Club of Cochin Global, Ernakulam. The GH has allocated space at its building to set up the HMB.
The logo of the proposed milk bank was released by the minister at the event. A second milk bank will be also setup in Thrissur Jubilee Mission Hospital.

The HMB will be set up in Ernakulam GH within two months. It aims to avail breast milk to newborn babies who are not being breastfed by their own mothers who may be sick, deceased or due to insufficient production of breast milk.

Kerala will soon have its first Human Milk Bank. An MoU was signed between the Ernakulam General Hospital and Rotary Club Cochin Global, which funds the project, in the presence of health minister KK Shailaja on Sunday at Ernakulam govt guest house
